  <span class="eyebrow">Panel upgrades</span>
  <h1>
    Electrical panel upgrades that create room, clarity, and safer long-term
    capacity
  </h1>
  <p>
    Panel work is often where bigger electrical decisions begin. Whether the
    issue is a crowded breaker layout, not enough amperage for new equipment, a
    remodel that needs new circuits, or an aging panel that no longer fits the
    property, the right upgrade should solve the real capacity problem and make
    the system easier to understand after the work is done.
  </p>
  <ul class="checklist">
    <li>
      Strong fit for remodels, EV charger prep, generator planning, and service
      modernization
    </li>
    <li>Clear labeling and cleaner organization after the upgrade</li>
    <li>Capacity decisions tied to actual loads and future use</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="cta-row">
  <a
    class="btn btn-primary"
    href="/booking"
    data-cta="booking"
    data-cta-location="hero"
    >Request Scheduling</a
  ><a
    class="btn btn-ghost"
    href="tel:+16163347159"
    data-cta="call"
    data-cta-location="hero"
    >Call / Text</a
  >
</div>

</section>

<section class="container section-stack section-stack--tight">
  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <h2>Signs a panel upgrade may be the right move</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>
          Breaker spaces are full or tandem breakers are doing too much work
        </li>
        <li>
          New loads like EV charging, HVAC, or workshop equipment need capacity
        </li>
        <li>
          Existing labeling is unclear and service calls take longer than they
          should
        </li>
        <li>
          Older equipment is showing wear, heat, nuisance trips, or poor
          organization
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h2>What the scope usually includes</h2>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>
          Review of service size, panel condition, grounding, and future circuit
          needs
        </li>
        <li>
          Breaker and feeder planning based on realistic present and near-term
          loads
        </li>
        <li>Cleaner circuit organization, labeling, and final testing</li>
        <li>
          Coordination around inspections and related corrective work when
          needed
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <span class="eyebrow">Why this page matters</span>
  <h2>
    A panel upgrade is usually a planning decision, not just a hardware swap
  </h2>
  <p>
    The most expensive part of panel work is often not the panel itself. It is
    the consequence of getting the planning wrong: not leaving room for future
    circuits, undersizing for an incoming EV charger, failing to clean up old
    circuit identification, or replacing equipment without solving the reason
    the system felt strained in the first place. A good upgrade creates order,
    supports the next project, and makes future troubleshooting easier.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="container section-stack">
  <span class="eyebrow">Typical project flow</span>
  <div class="process-grid">
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>1</strong>
      <h3>Capacity review</h3>
      <p>
        Understand current loads, near-term additions, and whether service size
        or panel space is the main constraint.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>2</strong>
      <h3>Scope planning</h3>
      <p>
        Map what needs to move, what should be corrected, and how the upgraded
        panel should be organized.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>3</strong>
      <h3>Upgrade execution</h3>
      <p>
        Replace equipment, land circuits cleanly, and complete labeling with
        future serviceability in mind.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="process-step">
      <strong>4</strong>
      <h3>Final walkthrough</h3>
      <p>
        Confirm operation, explain key changes, and connect the upgrade to
        future projects like charging or backup power.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

